Question_Text: You're going away for the weekend. How do you prepare the night before?
Option_A_Text: I mentally run through what I need and pack once — essentials are covered.
Option_B_Text: I write a full list, check everything off, repack a few times, still feel uneasy.
Option_C_Text: I throw things in last minute and trust it'll be fine.
Option_D_Text: I pack, unpack, and get overwhelmed deciding what I even need.

Question_Text: A close friend unintentionally hurts your feelings. How do you respond?
Option_A_Text: I won't say anything — they'll figure it out or I'll quietly move on.
Option_B_Text: I'll express it — maybe now, maybe later — but it will come out.
Option_C_Text: I react suddenly, then second-guess if I was overdramatic.
Option_D_Text: I feel stuck about whether I should say something or not.

Question_Text: You walk into a room full of strangers. What do you do?
Option_A_Text: I observe quietly, scan the room, and engage when it makes strategic sense.
Option_B_Text: I tune into the energy — I might light up the room or stay quiet, depending how I feel.
Option_C_Text: I pause and wait for someone to approach — I'm not sure how to show up.
Option_D_Text: I keep switching between acting confident and feeling unsure — I want to be seen but don't know how.

Question_Text: You've committed to waking up at 6am for a week. Day 3, you're exhausted. What happens?
Option_A_Text: I stick to it. Fatigue doesn't override commitment unless it's serious.
Option_B_Text: I ask myself if the reason still matters — if not, I adjust without guilt.
Option_C_Text: I sleep in, feel bad, and try again tomorrow.
Option_D_Text: I feel torn — I want to keep going but can't force myself either.

Question_Text: You've completed a project and it performs well. How do you feel about it?
Option_A_Text: If the result is strong, I'm satisfied — no need to change anything.
Option_B_Text: I immediately wonder how it could have been even better.
Option_C_Text: I feel good but uneasy — maybe I missed something important.
Option_D_Text: I feel proud for a moment, then wonder if I was just lucky.

Question_Text: You're pursuing a goal no one else has achieved. How do you think about it?
Option_A_Text: I need to see a path or example — otherwise I'm not sure it's achievable.
Option_B_Text: Even if no one's done it, I know it's possible — I just need the steps.
Option_C_Text: I doubt myself, but I still try in case it works out.
Option_D_Text: I switch between confidence and confusion depending on the day.

Question_Text: You're about to launch a new offer in 2 weeks. How would your opposite decide what to focus on first?
Option_A_Text: Identify the core bottlenecks and map out the sequence to remove them
Option_B_Text: Jump between setup, content, and branding — depending on what feels most urgent
Option_C_Text: Ask others what they think should happen first and go with consensus
Option_D_Text: None of these reflect how my opposite would operate

Question_Text: A peer gives you tough feedback on your recent launch. How would your opposite respond?
Option_A_Text: Shrug it off publicly but internalize it deeply and avoid the peer next time
Option_B_Text: Say thank you, then try to adjust only the parts you agree with emotionally
Option_C_Text: Break down the feedback, sort it into categories, and adjust where it makes sense
Option_D_Text: None of these reflect how my opposite would operate

Question_Text: You've brought on a new team member who isn't delivering as expected. How would your opposite handle it?
Option_A_Text: Overcompensate by taking on their tasks and quietly hoping they improve
Option_B_Text: Give vague feedback while focusing on keeping morale high
Option_C_Text: Review expectations, pinpoint where the breakdown occurred, and restructure their workflow
Option_D_Text: None of these reflect how my opposite would operate

Question_Text: A long-term partnership feels exciting but unclear. How would your opposite approach the next step?
Option_A_Text: Wait to see how things evolve and trust it will clarify naturally
Option_B_Text: Say yes quickly, then figure it out as they go
Option_C_Text: Clarify objectives, roles, and measurable outcomes before committing
Option_D_Text: None of these reflect how my opposite would operate

Question_Text: A team member keeps missing deadlines. How would your opposite handle this?
Option_A_Text: Set up a review system to track accountability and outline next steps
Option_B_Text: Avoid confrontation and work around them instead
Option_C_Text: Assume they need more motivation and give them a pep talk
Option_D_Text: None of these reflect how my opposite would operate

Question_Text: You just wrapped a high-revenue campaign. What would your opposite focus on next?
Option_A_Text: Break down what worked and rebuild the system for repeatability
Option_B_Text: Start planning a new direction without reviewing results
Option_C_Text: Celebrate with the team and move on instinctively
Option_D_Text: None of these reflect how my opposite would operate

Question_Text: You've just had an idea you're excited about, but you're not sure how to begin. What's your first move?
Option_A_Text: I outline the steps from A to Z and start mapping the tools or systems I'd need to deliver it properly.
Option_B_Text: I write down everything I'd want it to include — even if I don't know how I'll get there yet.
Option_C_Text: I sketch out a basic version and start testing how it might work.
Option_D_Text: I pause to define the real problem it solves before I do anything else.

Question_Text: You've written a rough outline for a course or product. What do you naturally do next?
Option_A_Text: I check if each part connects logically and improve the structure before building anything.
Option_B_Text: I open up a tool and start creating the first few sections to see how it feels in action.
Option_C_Text: I make a checklist of every component and start working through it step-by-step.
Option_D_Text: I stop to re-question the core idea: 'Is this still the right thing to build?'

Question_Text: You've sketched out a new service or program. A friend asks you, 'How will it work?' What do you instinctively describe first?
Option_A_Text: The reason I'm offering it and what kind of transformation it's built to deliver.
Option_B_Text: The tools, steps, and delivery flow — I explain exactly how someone would go through it.
Option_C_Text: The logic behind the framework — why each part exists and how it links to the bigger picture.
Option_D_Text: I say, 'Let me show you'—then pull up a mock-up or system to demonstrate.

Question_Text: You've joined a mastermind group, and they're brainstorming ways to improve their businesses. What's your natural way of contributing?
Option_A_Text: I start drawing on the whiteboard — mapping steps, bottlenecks, or a better way to do things.
Option_B_Text: I stay quiet until I've listened deeply, then share a clear plan or observation that changes the direction.
Option_C_Text: I suggest ways they could simplify and scale — I'm always thinking about leverage and strategy.
Option_D_Text: I ask focused questions to help them think better, and naturally start outlining the structure for them.

Question_Text: You've got a notebook full of business ideas. What's your natural approach to choosing which one to act on?
Option_A_Text: I compare them logically — which one solves the biggest problem, and which has the most potential to scale?
Option_B_Text: I test parts of a few ideas to see which one feels smooth to build and execute.
Option_C_Text: I think about which idea has the clearest delivery process — I like knowing exactly how I'd create and deliver it.
Option_D_Text: I ask myself which idea is easiest to explain to others — if I can map it cleanly, I know I'll build it well.

Question_Text: A friend asks for help turning their business idea into something real. You agree. What's your instinctive first step?
Option_A_Text: I draw out a clear plan — what needs to be done, in what order, and by when.
Option_B_Text: I offer to help set up the first few tools or tech pieces to get things moving.
Option_C_Text: I start mapping the entire process into systems — I want everything running smoothly early on.
Option_D_Text: I ask them to describe their end goal in one sentence, then figure out how to reverse-engineer it from there.

Question_Text: You're given a blank room and asked to design it however you want — no deadline, no instructions, just freedom. What do you naturally do first?
Option_A_Text: I stand in the space and feel what it needs. Then I begin placing things intuitively.
Option_B_Text: I imagine the finished look instantly, then begin collecting images or pieces to match the vision.
Option_C_Text: I begin sketching it out in a step-by-step plan so I don't waste energy.
Option_D_Text: I overthink each decision and delay starting until I'm sure it'll look right.

Question_Text: Think back to your school years. How did you usually approach a long homework assignment?
Option_A_Text: I waited until inspiration hit, then worked in a creative sprint.
Option_B_Text: I wrote and rewrote sections until it was perfect — even if it was last minute.
Option_C_Text: I mapped the sections, added energy when I felt aligned, and adjusted as I went.
Option_D_Text: I needed to be alone, clear the space, and feel right before even beginning.

Question_Text: When asked to clean your room or organise your space as a child, what best describes your approach?
Option_A_Text: I did it in one big emotional burst — the chaos would build until I had to act.
Option_B_Text: I made a plan or system first, then tackled it piece by piece.
Option_C_Text: I felt overwhelmed unless the mood or energy felt right.
Option_D_Text: I cleaned while imagining how I wanted it to look when done — I needed to see it first.

Question_Text: You're learning a new skill (e.g., cooking, driving, drawing). Which learning pattern is most natural for you?
Option_A_Text: I research first, then repeat steps until it feels mastered.
Option_B_Text: I learn by doing — I just start and fix mistakes as I go.
Option_C_Text: I learn when I feel connected to what I'm doing — if the energy's off, I can't focus.
Option_D_Text: I see the end result in my head first, then I try to recreate it immediately.
